  "prompt": "Can tax exemption be availed on tax saving FD for the entire tenure of 5 years by investing 1.5 lakhs in the 1st year?",
  "response": "In India, tax-saving fixed deposits (FDs) fall under Section 80C of the Income Tax Act. When you invest in a tax-saving FD, you can claim a deduction of up to \u20b91.5 lakhs in a financial year, but this is applicable for the investment made in that specific financial year.\n\nOnce you invest \u20b91.5 lakhs in a tax-saving FD in the first year, you can claim the deduction for that amount in that financial year, but you cannot claim additional tax deductions for the same investment in subsequent years. The tax-saving FD has a lock-in period of 5 years, and while your principal remains locked in, the tax benefit is limited to the initial amount invested during the financial year of investment.\n\nSo, to summarize:\n- You can claim a deduction of \u20b91.5 lakhs for the year in which you make that investment.\n- The tax benefit is not repeated for the entire duration of 5 years; it only applies to the year in which the investment was made.\n\nIt's essential to keep this in mind while planning your investments and tax strategy. If you are looking for ongoing tax benefits, you may need to consider making new investments in subsequent years, within the limits of Section 80C.",
